26:18.326 --> 26:21.162
<i>talked to Jack and persuaded</i>
<i>him to go to the van,</i>

26:21.454 --> 26:24.124
<i>'cause there were certain sexual things</i>
<i>that he enjoyed.</i>

26:24.499 --> 26:27.252
Bam! She shoots him
in the back of the head.

26:28.378 --> 26:31.923
<i>And she said I had a hell</i>
<i>of a time cutting the head off.</i>

26:34.092 --> 26:36.011
<i>Jack Murray's head was never found.</i>

26:39.222 --> 26:41.266
FLOYD: <i>Carol's confessions were chilling.</i>

26:41.933 --> 26:44.811
<i>But police still needed</i>
<i>to corroborate her story</i>

26:44.894 --> 26:46.938
<i>if they were going to convict Doug Clark,</i>

26:47.022 --> 26:48.690
<i>who claimed he was innocent.</i>

26:50.358 --> 26:52.444
<i>And they had somewhere to look.</i>

26:53.069 --> 26:57.198
The garage where Carol said
she and Doug took the two girls,

26:57.282 --> 26:59.743
<i>Gina Marano and Cynthia Chandler,</i>

26:59.826 --> 27:01.119
<i>after he'd killed them.</i>

27:02.037 --> 27:04.456
We responded to the garage that night.

27:07.250 --> 27:09.878
<i>Upon entry to the garage</i>
<i>with the light on,</i>

27:10.003 --> 27:12.422
<i>I noticed there was drag marks</i>
<i>on the floor</i>

27:12.505 --> 27:15.675
<i>leading to the left rear corner</i>
<i>of the garage</i>

27:16.343 --> 27:18.386
<i>which corresponded with the information</i>

27:18.470 --> 27:19.554
that Carol had given us

27:19.638 --> 27:21.598
about where he had taken the two sisters.

27:21.681 --> 27:23.516
<i>I knew there was a pretty good chance</i>

27:23.600 --> 27:25.226
<i>that we could recover evidence.</i>

27:26.394 --> 27:27.520
(camera shutter clicks)

27:28.188 --> 27:31.900
<i>During the blood samples</i>
<i>that were taken by the crime lab</i>

27:31.983 --> 27:33.818
is when we saw the boot print.

27:33.902 --> 27:36.196
<i>Of course, it was all under the blood.</i>

27:37.530 --> 27:40.450
FLOYD:
<i>This was a really significant discovery.</i>

27:40.533 --> 27:43.703
If this boot print, barely
visible on the garage floor,

27:43.787 --> 27:46.039
could be safely collected as evidence,

27:46.247 --> 27:50.168
detectives might be able to tie
the crime scene to Doug Clark.

27:50.251 --> 27:52.712
The on-scene criminalist
told Detective Garcia

27:52.796 --> 27:54.923
that attempting to collect this boot print

27:55.006 --> 27:56.675
does came with huge risk.

27:56.758 --> 27:59.177
She told us if I lift the print,

27:59.260 --> 28:01.471
it will destroy the blood value in it.

28:01.888 --> 28:03.848
I said that's okay,
we've got plenty of blood.

28:04.641 --> 28:06.142
She lifts the print.

28:07.102 --> 28:09.062
<i>And it's a nice beautiful boot print.</i>

28:11.022 --> 28:12.816
MURPHY: <i>Now the police have</i>
<i>some hard evidence.</i>

28:12.899 --> 28:16.361
But what happened next
was a complete surprise

28:16.444 --> 28:19.364
and became a turning point
in the entire investigation.

28:19.906 --> 28:22.534
GARCIA: <i>So, the next day, Doug Clark,</i>

28:22.617 --> 28:24.911
<i>he had been brought up into the squad room</i>

28:24.994 --> 28:26.746
<i>to get some blood samples.</i>

28:27.122 --> 28:28.289
<i>So, we're sitting there</i>

28:28.873 --> 28:31.501
<i>and we're catching up</i>
<i>on our logs and reports,</i>

28:32.043 --> 28:34.838
and Doug's sitting
at the front of the squad room

28:35.338 --> 28:38.800
and he's very condescending,
very arrogant.

28:39.050 --> 28:40.301
And he's just looking at everybody.

28:40.385 --> 28:41.761
And you could tell he thought, man,

28:42.053 --> 28:44.013
<i>what a bunch of stupid guys</i>
<i>these are, you know.</i>

28:44.389 --> 28:47.726
<i>And then Doug Clark picked up his feet,</i>

28:47.809 --> 28:50.270
<i>put them on the desk,</i>
<i>and crossed his legs.</i>

28:53.273 --> 28:54.774
<i>And we can't believe our eyes.</i>

28:57.235 --> 28:59.154
<i>That night before,</i>
<i>just hours before, we had seen</i>

28:59.237 --> 29:02.657
<i>that very same footprint</i>
<i>on the floor of the garage.</i>

29:03.032 --> 29:06.828
<i>So, we literally ran up to the desk</i>
<i>and take your boots off.</i>

29:06.911 --> 29:08.747
<i>And they were booked into evidence.</i>

29:10.957 --> 29:12.625
MURPHY: <i>The boots were a major</i>
<i>breakthrough,</i>

29:12.709 --> 29:14.252
<i>certainly enough to make an arrest,</i>

29:14.335 --> 29:16.421
<i>but detectives still wanted more.</i>

29:16.504 --> 29:19.340
One of the hallmarks of serial killers
is they keep trophies

29:19.632 --> 29:22.302
<i>and in this case, police really felt</i>

29:22.385 --> 29:24.679
<i>that Doug Clark</i>
<i>would have kept those guns,</i>

29:24.763 --> 29:27.682
the instrumentality of murder as trophies,

29:27.766 --> 29:30.018
and so they set out to find them.

29:30.977 --> 29:32.979
GARCIA:
<i>We started figuring, well, Doug's job</i>

29:33.062 --> 29:35.064
<i>was at the Jergens manufacturing plant.</i>

29:35.148 --> 29:36.941
<i>He was in charge of the boiler room.</i>

29:38.276 --> 29:40.904
So I went to Jergens manufacturing plant

29:40.987 --> 29:42.739
to start looking at that boiler room,

29:42.822 --> 29:44.657
every little nook and cranny,

29:45.074 --> 29:46.576
and try to find those guns.

29:49.621 --> 29:50.955
<i>The top of the wall,</i>

29:51.372 --> 29:53.374
<i>one of the bricks came loose,</i>

29:54.542 --> 29:56.878
and there's the pouch
with the two .25 calibers.

29:59.923 --> 30:01.382
<i>The murder weapons were there.</i>

30:02.175 --> 30:04.427
<i>The guns are registered to Carol Bundy.</i>

30:05.470 --> 30:07.639
That was... that was gold.

30:10.308 --> 30:13.853
♪♪

30:14.229 --> 30:16.898
FLOYD: <i>Doug Clark was charged</i>
<i>with six murders</i>

30:16.981 --> 30:19.108
and to the surprise of the court,

30:19.651 --> 30:22.821
<i>decided to represent himself at trial.</i>

30:24.405 --> 30:28.243
FARR: <i>Doug's trial was</i>
<i>a circus beyond all circuses.</i>

30:29.369 --> 30:31.621
Doug was so insulting
and profane in his language

30:32.038 --> 30:33.456
<i>that he had to be gagged</i>

30:33.540 --> 30:35.917
<i>and taken from the court</i>
<i>a number of times.</i>

30:36.376 --> 30:39.212
<i>At one point, he was in a</i>
<i>holding cell next to the court</i>

30:39.295 --> 30:40.964
where he could hear the proceedings,

30:41.047 --> 30:43.466
and he was banging on the wall yelling.

30:44.217 --> 30:46.302
<i>Carol pleaded guilty to two murders.</i>

30:46.928 --> 30:51.349
She was sentenced
to two terms of 25 years to life

30:51.432 --> 30:52.934
for the murders of Jack Murray

30:53.017 --> 30:55.895
and a little prostitute they named Kathy.

30:56.437 --> 30:58.231
<i>Clark received the death penalty</i>

30:58.731 --> 31:00.733
<i>for the murders of six of the victims.</i>

31:01.317 --> 31:04.070
<i>He's still there in prison today.</i>

31:08.241 --> 31:09.909
GARCIA: <i>People like Carol Bundy</i>
<i>and Doug Clark</i>

31:09.993 --> 31:13.246
<i>that meet each other,</i>
<i>there's a certain chemistry.</i>

31:14.247 --> 31:17.709
<i>Carol Bundy, I don't personally think</i>
<i>would have ever killed anybody</i>

31:17.792 --> 31:20.128
had it not been for Doug Clark.

31:21.212 --> 31:24.132
JAMES ALAN FOX:
<i>Carol Bundy was a vulnerable individual,</i>

31:25.758 --> 31:27.719
<i>and she was a willing partner,</i>

31:28.386 --> 31:29.762
willing to help him

31:29.846 --> 31:32.640
with his murders to hold onto her man.

31:33.057 --> 31:34.517
She would do anything for love.

31:35.018 --> 31:37.937
I don't think Carol had any remorse.

31:38.938 --> 31:40.857
<i>And she was ill, she had diabetes.</i>

31:40.940 --> 31:43.526
<i>She had heart trouble.</i>
<i>She was not a healthy woman.</i>

31:43.610 --> 31:46.112
But I think it made her important.

31:46.195 --> 31:50.033
I think the Sunset Strip
killings made Carol's name.

31:54.787 --> 31:57.373
Many of these cases came to a head

31:57.457 --> 31:58.666
around the same time.

31:58.750 --> 32:01.085
In fact, the Sunset Strip killings

32:01.169 --> 32:02.587
<i>and the Hillside Strangler killings,</i>

32:02.670 --> 32:04.589
<i>those trials were happening</i>
<i>in the same building</i>

32:04.672 --> 32:06.049
<i>at the exact same time.</i>

32:06.132 --> 32:09.177
But what authorities did not consider
is that decades later,

32:09.260 --> 32:10.511
they would still be fighting

32:10.595 --> 32:13.014
to keep some of these killers behind bars.

32:16.017 --> 32:17.685
<i>Bobby Joe Maxwell had been convicted</i>

32:17.769 --> 32:20.688
<i>of the Skid Row Stabber murders in 1984.</i>

32:20.772 --> 32:23.399
Almost 35 years later, in 2018,

32:23.483 --> 32:25.151
his conviction was overturned on appeal.

32:26.945 --> 32:28.696
ROBERT GRACE: <i>Bobby Joe Maxwell felt that</i>

32:28.780 --> 32:31.366
<i>he was innocent of the charges.</i>

32:33.493 --> 32:36.746
The key witness in the case
was later discredited.

32:37.622 --> 32:39.832
<i>Finally, a federal appeals court</i>

32:39.916 --> 32:41.834
<i>overturned the conviction.</i>

32:44.170 --> 32:47.382
We were battling in court
in, uh, pretrial motions,

32:47.465 --> 32:50.093
<i>and then Bobby Joe Maxwell</i>
<i>fell into a coma.</i>

32:50.176 --> 32:52.553
<i>Due to his medical condition,</i>

32:53.262 --> 32:54.806
we dropped the charges against him

32:54.889 --> 32:56.474
<i>just before he died.</i>

32:58.309 --> 33:01.229
<i>It doesn't mean that</i>
<i>Bobby Joe Maxwell was guilty,</i>

33:01.312 --> 33:03.022
it doesn't mean that he was not guilty.

33:03.106 --> 33:06.401
It just means that given
the circumstances at the time

33:06.859 --> 33:08.486
we chose not to go forward.

33:13.282 --> 33:15.827
TOM LANGE: <i>Just because they receive</i>
<i>some kind of release</i>

33:15.910 --> 33:17.495
doesn't mean they didn't kill.

33:18.246 --> 33:19.747
It doesn't mean they didn't do it.

33:20.248 --> 33:22.125
Cops can only do what cops do.

33:22.667 --> 33:25.962
<i>They can't do what prosecutors do,</i>
<i>defense attorneys do,</i>

33:26.045 --> 33:29.841
<i>the judge does, the jury does,</i>
<i>what the media says.</i>

33:29.924 --> 33:31.217
<i>You can't do any of that.</i>

33:31.592 --> 33:32.969
You can only do what the cop does.

33:33.594 --> 33:35.430
And the cops did their job.

33:35.513 --> 33:37.932
I went to trial on the evidence
on this thing

33:38.016 --> 33:39.684
up to almost three,
three and a half years ago.

33:41.060 --> 33:43.146
<i>I was still going on this thing</i>
<i>40 years later.</i>

33:45.106 --> 33:46.941
<i>If he'd have lived,</i>
<i>he could have been retried.</i>

33:47.442 --> 33:49.652
<i>But he died, and that was the end of it.</i>

33:53.656 --> 33:55.992
MURPHY: <i>Rodney Alcala</i>
<i>who was The Dating Game Killer</i>

33:56.075 --> 33:59.037
was convicted of Robin Samsoe's
murder in 1980,

33:59.579 --> 34:02.373
but this case was far from over.

34:03.624 --> 34:06.002
<i>This man was incredibly prolific.</i>

34:06.377 --> 34:08.796
But remember, he's arrested in 1979,

34:08.880 --> 34:11.049
and all they knew about him for sure was

34:11.132 --> 34:13.968
<i>the rape and kidnapping of Tali Shapiro.</i>

34:15.219 --> 34:17.513
So, at the time he's arrested
for Robin Samsoe,

34:18.306 --> 34:21.434
<i>the only known murder that</i>
<i>he committed was Robin Samsoe.</i>

34:22.685 --> 34:25.521
<i>It wasn't until 2005 or 2006</i>

34:25.605 --> 34:27.231
<i>when we started getting his DNA hits</i>

34:27.315 --> 34:28.649
<i>where people started to realize</i>

34:28.733 --> 34:32.612
what a massively prolific
serial killer Rodney Alcala was.

34:35.740 --> 34:39.452
<i>Forensic science really</i>
<i>caught up to Rodney Alcala.</i>

34:40.745 --> 34:42.663
GINA SATRIANO:
<i>Using this brand-new technology</i>

34:42.747 --> 34:44.373
<i>that did not exist in the '70s,</i>

34:44.457 --> 34:47.085
the evidence from many different
cold cases

34:47.168 --> 34:49.337
<i>was analyzed for DNA.</i>

34:50.880 --> 34:53.466
<i>One by one, a connection is made</i>

34:53.549 --> 34:56.302
<i>from Rodney Alcala to Charlotte Lamb.</i>

34:57.095 --> 34:58.387
<i>Then Jill Barcomb.</i>

35:00.056 --> 35:02.391
How many people did Rodney Alcala kill?

35:02.475 --> 35:05.186
<i>What we know is at the time</i>
<i>he went on </i>The Dating Game,

35:05.269 --> 35:06.562
he killed at least eight.

35:06.646 --> 35:08.689
<i>But the actual real number is far higher.</i>

35:10.358 --> 35:11.984
There is information that he
had gone to Europe

35:12.068 --> 35:12.985
after he had been paroled.

35:13.069 --> 35:16.197
<i>He was permitted to drive</i>
<i>across the country multiple times.</i>

35:16.280 --> 35:19.325
As a prosecutor, you realize
that you're looking at a guy

35:19.408 --> 35:21.828
<i>who has not just killed</i>
<i>the people you know about,</i>

35:21.911 --> 35:24.789
<i>he's killed dozens upon dozens of people</i>

35:24.872 --> 35:26.332
<i>over the course of his life.</i>

35:27.458 --> 35:31.629
The enormity of that is,
it's just kind of mind blowing.

35:32.338 --> 35:35.842
<i>Rodney Alcala died on July 24, 2021,</i>

35:35.925 --> 35:39.053
<i>while still on death row</i>
<i>in California prison.</i>

35:40.304 --> 35:43.307
Nobody ever needs to worry
about Rodney Alcala every again.

35:43.724 --> 35:48.146
<i>If there's a hell, Rodney Alcala had</i>
<i>a seat waiting for him.</i>

35:48.229 --> 35:49.897
♪♪

35:51.524 --> 35:54.569
♪♪

35:54.652 --> 35:58.197
♪♪

36:00.408 --> 36:03.411
STERLING NORRIS: <i>I don't think he feels</i>
<i>for one minute any remorse,</i>

36:03.494 --> 36:04.662
<i>uh, for any of this.</i>

36:05.079 --> 36:07.915
<i>Law enforcement took him off</i>
<i>the streets a bloody killer,</i>

36:07.999 --> 36:11.002
<i>uh, and I think he will go</i>
<i>to his execution that way.</i>

36:11.711 --> 36:15.590
MURPHY: <i>Fourteen years after he was</i>
<i>sentenced to death,</i>

36:15.673 --> 36:19.468
William Bonin was
finally up for execution.

36:21.053 --> 36:23.389
DAVID MCVICKER: <i>I got a phone call</i>
<i>one day when I was at work.</i>

36:23.472 --> 36:25.766
I heard that the execution was going on.

36:29.145 --> 36:31.647
David McVicker was the last victim

36:31.731 --> 36:33.149
that Bonin allowed to live.

36:34.817 --> 36:36.360
<i>He was looking for closure.</i>

36:37.612 --> 36:38.988
<i>That affected his whole life.</i>

36:40.489 --> 36:42.742
I wanted to change my mental videotape

36:42.825 --> 36:45.494
because I was having horrible nightmares
all the time.

36:45.578 --> 36:48.581
<i>I'm trying to keep busy</i>
<i>until the time comes.</i>

36:49.123 --> 36:52.210
<i>I-- this is a very,</i>
<i>very hard thing for me to do.</i>

36:52.293 --> 36:55.379
<i>It's, it's been very draining.</i>
<i>I haven't had sleep in days.</i>

36:55.463 --> 36:57.506
And I just thought that if I saw him die

36:57.590 --> 36:59.467
even though I don't want to see
an execution, you know,

36:59.550 --> 37:01.302
I don't want to see somebody die.

37:01.719 --> 37:03.971
But for him though,
it was a little bit different

37:04.055 --> 37:06.641
because he was killing me all the time.

37:06.724 --> 37:10.311
I wanted to see it just so I could change

37:10.394 --> 37:11.812
how I sleep at night.

37:12.730 --> 37:15.566
FLOYD: <i>William Bonin was finally set</i>
<i>to be executed</i>

37:15.650 --> 37:18.819
<i>on February 23, 1996.</i>

37:18.903 --> 37:22.240
Detective Robert Souza
was determined to be there,

37:22.615 --> 37:26.452
<i>but his partner, John St. John,</i>
<i>had already passed away.</i>

37:29.038 --> 37:31.707
SOUZA: <i>I showed up five o'clock</i>
<i>at the prison.</i>

37:34.377 --> 37:38.130
I get up there, I walk in
and the scene itself,

37:38.214 --> 37:41.300
<i>I always describe it</i>
<i>as somewhere between a wake</i>

37:41.926 --> 37:43.010
<i>and a wedding reception.</i>

37:43.094 --> 37:44.595
<i>It was very strange.</i>

37:45.054 --> 37:47.765
<i>All the ladies, the victims,</i>
<i>some of them I recognized,</i>

37:47.848 --> 37:51.394
victim's mothers wore pictures
of their sons

37:51.477 --> 37:52.937
who were victims on their dresses.

37:55.773 --> 37:56.941
They took us into the prison,

37:57.024 --> 37:59.026
myself and Sandy Miller,
one of the mothers.

37:59.652 --> 38:02.571
<i>Her son was murdered.</i>
<i>His name was Russell Rugh.</i>

38:03.614 --> 38:05.491
<i>She was devastated.</i>

38:06.242 --> 38:09.161
<i>It tore her apart to the core.</i>

38:10.705 --> 38:12.915
<i>Nobody's ever gonna bring me back my boy,</i>

38:12.999 --> 38:15.251
<i>any of the other kids. </i>(sobs)

38:15.334 --> 38:17.503
<i>The only thing different</i>
<i>is Bonin will be dead,</i>

38:17.586 --> 38:19.380
<i>and he can't hurt anybody else's.</i>

38:29.181 --> 38:31.183
SOUZA: <i>So we're all in there,</i>
<i>and the curtains were closed</i>

38:31.267 --> 38:33.185
<i>on the actual death chamber where he was.</i>

38:37.356 --> 38:39.025
MCVICKER: <i>They open up the curtains,</i>

38:40.693 --> 38:43.612
and I just wanted to see the evil go dead.

38:46.032 --> 38:50.119
The IV for the, uh, the triple injection
they give him

38:50.578 --> 38:52.455
<i>was all covered with a big bandage.</i>

38:52.872 --> 38:55.333
<i>He was just lying very still.</i>

38:56.334 --> 38:59.337
And then finally
his lips went phrrr, like that.

38:59.420 --> 39:01.464
And that was the last of his air
leaving his body.

39:04.967 --> 39:08.721
John had died just a year and a half
before Bonin was executed.

39:09.263 --> 39:11.057
<i>It would have meant a lot</i>
<i>to John to be there.</i>

39:14.185 --> 39:16.312
<i>I said what John asked me to say,</i>

39:18.606 --> 39:20.316
"Adios, you son of a bitch."

39:24.111 --> 39:27.656
When we all walked out after,
it was total silence.

39:28.199 --> 39:30.409
All the victims' families, they just,

39:30.493 --> 39:31.786
I don't think they knew how to act.

39:34.246 --> 39:36.499
They were relieved after all these years

39:37.041 --> 39:38.084
but were they happy?

39:38.167 --> 39:39.627
Were they-- was this enough for them?

39:39.710 --> 39:41.545
I didn't know what to say to these people.

39:41.629 --> 39:44.131
You know, I didn't want to say,
"Gee, that was good, huh?

39:44.215 --> 39:45.508
We got rid of that son of a bitch."

39:45.591 --> 39:47.593
You don't-- it's--it's not like that.

39:48.928 --> 39:51.138
I think he deserved a lot worse

39:51.222 --> 39:52.640
than what happened to him.

39:52.723 --> 39:54.350
And he lost his life, yeah.

39:54.433 --> 39:57.561
<i>But he had it easy</i>
<i>compared to everybody else.</i>

39:57.645 --> 39:59.063
<i>For him, it was like having a surgery.</i>

39:59.146 --> 40:00.815
<i>They put him to sleep, and he was gone.</i>

40:02.191 --> 40:04.360
And when the subject comes up,
I think about it

40:04.443 --> 40:06.612
and, you know, I have nightmares.

40:07.196 --> 40:09.532
It seems to almost never stop.

40:12.868 --> 40:16.414
SOUZA: <i>The Freeway Killer case,</i>
<i>it was more full circle to me.</i>

40:18.290 --> 40:20.626
I'd roll out on these dead body calls,

40:20.709 --> 40:22.169
and now I've taken it full circle

40:22.253 --> 40:25.464
to watch the guy who did it actually die.

40:27.258 --> 40:29.635
<i>I think today I realize</i>

40:29.718 --> 40:32.179
<i>the significance more than I did then.</i>

40:33.055 --> 40:36.267
We didn't have time to philosophize.
(chuckles)

40:36.350 --> 40:37.726
It was what we had to do.

40:38.269 --> 40:40.104
Let's get the son of a bitch, you know.

40:40.187 --> 40:41.856
Let's get him, let's get him
and put him in jail

40:41.939 --> 40:42.982
so he can't do it anymore.

40:44.150 --> 40:45.943
Pretty simple concept. And we did it.

40:55.661 --> 40:58.038
PATT MORRISON:
<i>When you go into all of these cases,</i>

40:59.415 --> 41:03.002
you see what was done to
the victims and their families.

41:06.213 --> 41:09.717
<i>These people had big dreams</i>
<i>to make a life for themselves.</i>

41:11.218 --> 41:14.972
<i>They deserved that chance to be</i>
<i>who they wanted to be.</i>

41:17.558 --> 41:19.393
<i>In the long run and the bigger sense,</i>

41:19.477 --> 41:21.979
<i>we should try not to remember the killers</i>

41:22.062 --> 41:23.689
<i>but to remember their victims.</i>

41:24.648 --> 41:28.319
<i>That should be the legacy of these times.</i>

41:30.571 --> 41:33.949
These cases are a form of trauma.

41:34.575 --> 41:36.827
And these guys that are working

41:37.661 --> 41:40.498
<i>for decades on these cases,</i>

41:40.581 --> 41:43.584
<i>no matter how gruff they come off,</i>

41:44.335 --> 41:46.170
<i>it's still inside of them.</i>

41:46.253 --> 41:47.505
<i>It will never go away.</i>

41:50.007 --> 41:53.135
There isn't that, um, high five moment.

41:53.469 --> 41:58.140
It's just almost sad, you know,
why does this exist?

42:01.101 --> 42:03.979
MURPHY: <i>These detectives really</i>
<i>were the pioneers</i>

42:04.063 --> 42:06.899
<i>of the modern era</i>
<i>of homicide investigations.</i>

42:07.983 --> 42:11.612
Being a prosecutor who reaped
the benefit of that for 17 years,

42:11.695 --> 42:15.282
I got to work with the,
with the second wave of these guys

42:16.033 --> 42:17.493
<i>who learned from the Tom Langes,</i>

42:17.576 --> 42:19.745
<i>who learned from these</i>
<i>dedicated detectives.</i>

42:22.915 --> 42:27.044
Today, in your life, you know people
that weren't murdered

42:27.378 --> 42:31.215
<i>because of the work that these detectives</i>
<i>accomplished.</i>

42:35.427 --> 42:38.097
The world is a far safer place today

42:38.180 --> 42:40.432
because of the work of those detectives.

42:42.643 --> 42:46.021
MICHAEL CONNELLY: <i>I don't think</i>
<i>we'll ever see that time again.</i>

42:48.232 --> 42:52.236
Yes, there is always
horrible tragic, uh, victims

42:52.319 --> 42:54.113
and, and stories like that,

42:54.196 --> 42:55.656
<i>but they could have been far worse</i>

42:55.739 --> 42:57.700
<i>if it was not for these detectives.</i>

43:05.291 --> 43:08.669
<i>They made this place safer</i>
<i>for many people through their work.</i>

43:09.086 --> 43:12.673
But I, I don't think they worry
about being thanked for it.

43:14.300 --> 43:15.759
<i>They all know what they did.</i>

43:16.969 --> 43:20.639
You know, looking back at this so-called
serial killing era,

43:21.140 --> 43:23.142
no matter how you want to talk about them,

43:23.225 --> 43:24.476
we solved every one of them.

43:24.560 --> 43:26.186
Every one of them been solved.

43:26.270 --> 43:28.856
LANGE: And I think
we all respected what we did

43:28.939 --> 43:31.066
for all those years was a success,

43:31.150 --> 43:33.861
and I think we're damn glad
we picked this as a career.

43:34.570 --> 43:37.281
Thinking back what I really feel
proud about is

43:37.364 --> 43:39.575
people wanted justice
for all those killings.

43:39.825 --> 43:41.577
Uh, that's what I feel good about.

43:42.286 --> 43:44.121
Personally, I think
I had a pretty good run.

43:44.580 --> 43:46.415
Uh, put a lot of bad guys in jail.

43:46.874 --> 43:48.250
I'm pretty proud to say that, uh,

43:48.334 --> 43:50.377
just about every murderer
I went after I got.

43:50.878 --> 43:52.504
I'm proud of the guys I worked with.

43:52.588 --> 43:54.840
Probably the finest group
of investigators anywhere.

43:56.258 --> 43:57.676
Pretty proud to be part of that.

43:58.302 --> 44:01.889
GARCIA: The most satisfaction I achieved
was solving the cases,

44:01.972 --> 44:04.975
closure for a lot of the
families that we could bring.

44:05.351 --> 44:07.811
Sometimes you, you talk to the mother,

44:07.895 --> 44:09.647
the father, the wife, whoever

44:10.064 --> 44:12.441
and after you solve the case
and they looked you in the eye

44:12.524 --> 44:14.109
and they go like this, thank you.

44:14.443 --> 44:16.070
And they mean it
from the bottom of their heart.

44:16.153 --> 44:17.071
LEFROIS: Yeah.

44:17.154 --> 44:20.115
And that means
more than anything in the world.

44:20.407 --> 44:23.243
I know a lot of cops from
the New York Police Department.

44:23.327 --> 44:26.246
I grew up in that back--
that part of the world.

44:26.330 --> 44:28.874
And I know what
the New York policemen thought

44:28.957 --> 44:31.168
of the Los Angeles Police Department.

44:31.251 --> 44:34.546
My buddy says,
you guys were the innovators.

44:34.630 --> 44:35.964
But most of all,

44:36.048 --> 44:38.967
you are the ultimate
investigative professionals

44:39.051 --> 44:40.135
in this country.

44:40.594 --> 44:41.970
I'm very proud of that.

44:42.680 --> 44:43.972
I love you guys.

44:44.056 --> 44:45.808
You're--you're brothers.

44:46.767 --> 44:47.768
You are the best.

44:48.394 --> 44:50.145
And I want to make a special toast

44:51.063 --> 44:52.523
to Robbery Homicide Division

44:52.606 --> 44:56.110
and all the detective agencies
in the City of Los Angeles.

44:56.193 --> 44:57.069
God bless you all.

44:57.152 --> 44:58.153
-Hear, hear.
-Cheers.

44:58.237 --> 44:59.196
-Hear, hear.
-Hear, hear.

45:07.955 --> 45:09.498
GROGAN: <i>I don't feel like, uh...</i>

45:10.416 --> 45:11.875
(clears throat, sniffles)

45:11.959 --> 45:13.419
the book has been closed.

45:13.502 --> 45:14.753
It never will.

45:16.130 --> 45:19.633
<i>I could never,</i>
<i>even to this day, understand</i>

45:20.008 --> 45:22.094
<i>why somebody would want to kill somebody.</i>

45:23.721 --> 45:27.057
Nobody deserves to die like that.

45:28.642 --> 45:30.269
<i>But there is justice.</i>

45:30.728 --> 45:33.564
Thank God. Justice was served.

45:34.314 --> 45:39.027
♪♪

